SIMPLE: weed
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Weed
<hw>Weed</hw> <pr>(w⟦emac⟧d)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>wede</ets>, AS. <ets>w⟦aemac⟧de</ets>, <ets>w⟦aemac⟧d</ets>; akin
to OS. <ets>w⟦amac⟧di</ets>, <ets>giw⟦amac⟧di</ets>, OFries,
<ets>w⟦emac⟧de</ets>, <ets>w⟦emac⟧d</ets>, OD. <ets>wade</ets>, OHG.
<ets>w⟦amac⟧t</ets>, Icel. <ets>v⟦amac⟧⟦edh⟧</ets>, Zend <ets>vadh</ets>
to clothe.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A garment; clothing; especially, an upper or outer
garment.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Lowly shepherd's <xex>weeds</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Spenser.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧Woman's <xex>weeds</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Shak.</au>
⟦ldquo⟧This beggar woman's <xex>weed</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Tennyson.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He on his bed sat, the soft <qex>weeds</qex> he wore⟦br⟧
Put off.</q> <rj><qau>Chapman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An article of dress worn in token of grief; a
mourning garment or badge; <as>as, he wore a <ex>weed</ex> on his
hat</as>; especially, in the plural, mourning garb, as of a woman;
<as>as, a widow's <ex>weeds</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In a mourning <qex>weed</qex>, with ashes upon her head, and tears
abundantly flowing.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Weed</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Weed
<hw>Weed</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A sudden illness or relapse, often
attended with fever, which attacks women in childbed.</def>
<mark>[Scot.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Weed</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Weed
<hw>Weed</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>weed</ets>, <ets>weod</ets>,
AS. <ets>we⟦oacute⟧d</ets>, <ets>wi⟦oacute⟧d</ets>, akin to OS.
<ets>wiod</ets>, LG. <ets>woden</ets> the stalks and leaves of
vegetables D. <ets>wieden</ets> to weed, OS.
<ets>wiod⟦omac⟧n</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Underbrush; low shrubs.</def> <mark>[Obs. or
Archaic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>One rushing forth out of the thickest <qex>weed</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A wild and wanton pard . . . ⟦br⟧
Crouched fawning in the <qex>weed</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any plant growing in cultivated ground to the injury
of the crop or desired vegetation, or to the disfigurement of the place;
an unsightly, useless, or injurious plant.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Too much manuring filled that field with <qex>weeds</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Denham.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The word has no definite application to any particular
plant, or species of plants. Whatever plants grow among corn or grass,
in hedges, or elsewhere, and are useless to man, injurious to crops, or
unsightly or out of place, are denominated <xex>weeds</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Fig.: Something unprofitable or troublesome;
anything useless.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Stock Breeding)</fld> <def>An animal unfit to breed
from.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Tobacco, or a cigar.</def> <mark>[Slang]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Weed hook</b></col>, <cd>a hook used for cutting away or
extirpating weeds.</cd> <rj><au>Tusser.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Weed</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Weed
<hw>Weed</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Weeded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Weeding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>we⟦oacute⟧dian</ets>.
See 3d <er>Weed</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To free from noxious plants; to clear of weeds;
<as>as, to <ex>weed</ex> corn or onions; to <ex>weed</ex> a
garden.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To take away, as noxious plants; to remove, as
something hurtful; to extirpate; -- commonly used with <ptcl>out</ptcl>;
<as>as, to <ex>weed out</ex> inefficiency from an enterprise</as>.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Weed</xex> up thyme.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Wise fathers . . . <qex>weeding</qex> from their children ill
things.</q> <rj><qau>Ascham.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Revenge is a kind of wild justice, which the more man's nature
runs to, the more ought law to <qex>weed</qex> it out.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To free from anything hurtful or
offensive.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>weeded</qex> the kingdom of such as were devoted to
Elaiana.</q> <rj><qau>Howell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Stock Breeding)</fld> <def>To reject as unfit for
breeding purposes.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Weeder</ent>⟦br⟧
